               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-250-person1479">
                  NEWCOMB 
                  MASON
               <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1479" type="surname" value="MASON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1479" type="given" value="NEWCOMB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1479" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an assistant to <rs id="t18340904-250-viclabel1399" type="occupation">Mr.</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-250-victim1478 t18340904-250-viclabel1399"></join> Tilbury, of <placeName id="t18340904-250-crimeloc1400">Mount-street, Grosvenor-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-250-crimeloc1400" type="placeName" value="Mount-street, Grosvenor-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-250-crimeloc1400" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-250-off1397 t18340904-250-crimeloc1400"></join> - I missed a great many saddles, bridles, and horse cloths - I was passing Mr. Langdon's shop last Wednesday, and saw this horse cloth, which I knew was my master's - I then traced it to the prisoner - the saddle was found at Lambeth - the prisoner had been a <rs id="t18340904-250-deflabel1401" type="occupation">helper in the stable</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-250-defend1477 t18340904-250-deflabel1401"></join>, but left nearly three months ago.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-250-person1480">
                  WILLIAM 
                  LANGDON
               <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1480" type="surname" value="LANGDON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1480" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1480" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a saddler. I bought the saddle and horse-cloth for 2l. 10s., of Marrs, whom I have known eight years.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-250-person1481">
                  EDWARD 
                  MARRS
               <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1481" type="surname" value="MARRS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1481" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1481" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I sold the saddle, horse-cloth, and this snap-bridle to Langdon - Riggs brought them into Mr. Jackson's yard, where I was at work - I did not know Riggs, but I came into the yard, and one of our men said,"Here is something to be sold, do you know a man that will buy them?" - I said, "Yes, if it is all right" - I took and sold them, and paid Riggs 30s., which was what he asked.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-250-person1482">
                  THOMAS 
                  RIGGS
               <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1482" type="surname" value="RIGGS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1482" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-250-person1482" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . One night, a fortnight before this, I met the prisoner at the corner of Duke-street - he asked if I was doing any thing - I said, "No;" he told me to go to him the next morning - I did so, and we went to a house, and had a pint of beer - he then said he had these things to sell for his brother, who was going out of town with a gentleman - I asked him if it was all right; he said it was - I took them to Mr. Jackson, and gave them to the ostler, who gave them to Marrs - I went back and asked the prisoner if it was all right; he said he would not have any thing to do with it without it was.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I found them in the Swan passage, near Mr. Tilbury's - I gave them to Riggs to sell - he came back, and said he had sold them for 26s. - he gave me 25s. and we spent 1s. - I gave him 4s. for his trouble.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340904-250-verdict1402" type="verdictDescription">
